					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/captain-kirby" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(3440103); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=3440103&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610204538" alt="Captain Kirby" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=3440103)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/captain-kirby" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(3440103); return false;" >Captain Kirby</a></span> <span class="odate time_1603901075 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">28 Oct 2020 16:04</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-4806125">
									

<p>This piece has improved since the first draft I read, but it still&#8230; like it still felt like it fell flat for me.</p>
<div class="collapsible-block">
<div class="collapsible-block-folded"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">+&nbsp;show&nbsp;block</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded" style="display:none">
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded-link"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">–&nbsp;hide&nbsp;block</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-content">
<p>First of all, we spend about a third of the article before we even see the food. This third is spent giving us some character development (which is fine) and a lot of imagery of logistics which I felt really bogged down the pacing of the story. There's a mystery that's promised to the reader in the beginning, but the following passages don't do much in the way of ratcheting tension around that mystery. Mostly because the imagery feels disjoint from the nature of &quot;what is up with the food?&quot;. Sure, there's some unexplained oddities but the details about the room and the trek there do not make me anymore curious about the food itself.</p>
<p>I think the flashbacks are definitely better at getting across the main theme, but I really wish this had varied the types of interactions more. They all feel like they play out the same &quot;I could have reached out to someone, but I didn't&quot;, which could've been mixed up by changing the stakes (maybe instead of a romantic bond maybe he could've offered to reach out to help). I understand that the third one is not necessarily romantic, but its so vague and ambiguous what he is failing to reach out for that it didn't really feel like a variation.</p>
<p>I actually liked the parental one in the beginning for variation, we don't get a lot of expansion on that, so again I didn't really latch onto it as well.</p>
<p>So, like coming into the ending I will be honest, I didn't feel particularly invested in this character. I think it has something to do with how direct the messaging is, which I know is something I brought up but I was hoping it would be addressed by reworking the flashbacks rather than just telling the reader directly. I prefer this to the theme being unclear, but it still doesn't suck me into the piece.</p>
<p>But really, what gets me about this article is the same thing that gets me about the other Waldon Studio format: the use of the overall review at the end feels like it actively undermines the emotionality of the piece.</p>
<p>The last thing the reader is left with isn't &quot;this is my last food review&quot; or &quot;A life changing experience that I would not wish upon anyone&quot;. The last words are &quot;Four stars&quot;. I believe the last version of this I read made the experience one star which made much more sense to me. Mostly because, this is what you're ending on, and apparently this &quot;life changing experience&quot; was not enough to elicit either extreme of the spectrum. The idea that there could be more in the tank, that there is something for this man above &quot;losing his passion for food&quot; that he can't bring himself to use either extreme of the scale actively undercuts the intense emotions we're supposed to be feeling at the end of the piece.</p>
<p>In fact, saying it was four stars would imply he enjoyed the whole affair, which again, does not track.</p>
<p>Even if it is because he's only rating the food and not the whole experience, such a half-measured line feels like a disservice to the piece, and heavily cheapens the emotions we feel prior.</p>
<p>-1</p>
<p>See, it I had ended this comment on a novote, it would've undercut how strongly I feel about the piece.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>

							</div>

								
					
